<p>It&#8217;s <a href="https://www.openaccessweek.org/about" target="_blank" rel="noopener">International Open Access Week</a>.<span id="more-55377"></span></p>
<p><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" class="wp-image-55379 aligncenter" src="https://dailynous.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/open-banner-1024x571.png" alt="" width="718" height="400" srcset="https://dailynous.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/open-banner-1024x571.png 1024w, https://dailynous.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/open-banner-300x167.png 300w, https://dailynous.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/open-banner-768x428.png 768w, https://dailynous.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/open-banner-400x223.png 400w, https://dailynous.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/open-banner.png 1400w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 718px) 100vw, 718px" /></p>
<p>In honor of the occasion, I invite those who have authored or edited an open access book in philosophy to share it in the comments here, with a link to where it is available.</p>
<p>Open Access Week is organized by <a href="https://sparcopen.org/who-we-are/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">SPARC</a>, a nonprofit advocacy organization that supports open systems for research. According to them, the week</p>
<p style="padding-left: 40px;"><em>is an opportunity for the academic and research community to continue to learn about the potential benefits of Open Access, to share what theyâ€™ve learned with colleagues, and to help inspire wider participation in helping to make Open Access a new norm in scholarship and research.</em></p>
<p>So, authors and editors, list your open access books. Reflections on the experience and effects of publishing an open access book are welcome, too.</p>
